article.headline: Prince's 25 pace No. 13 Rutgers in romp of Army
article.linkText: No. 13 Rutgers opens tourney with rout of Army
article.story:
NEW YORK -- Growing up in New York, Epiphanny Prince has always been comfortable playing in Madison Square Garden.

The Brooklyn native was instrumental in leading her high school to four straight public school championships playing at Madison Square Garden. On Sunday, Prince scored 25 points and Kia Vaughn added a season-high 12 to help Rutgers (No. 13 ESPN/USA Today, No. 14 AP) beat Army 59-38 in the first game of the Maggie Dixon Classic at MSG.

"I always think of the Garden floor as my home floor and I try to be aggressive," Prince said.

Rutgers (6-2) had struggled to win its last three games, averaging 22 turnovers in the victories. The Scarlet Knights only had 11 against Army.

"We were trying to do a couple of things well," Rutgers coach C. Vivian Stringer said. "We cut down the turnovers and we made a much more conscious effort to take care of the basketball."

They also hadn't been getting much from Vaughn, who was only averaging 8.1 points. The senior center, who went to high school a block from the Garden, was even benched in a victory over Georgia.

"Unlike 'Piph I didn't get many chances to play here [MSG] and it's nice," Vaughn said.

On Sunday, Rutgers made an effort to get Vaughn involved early. She scored eight of the team's first 10 points as the Scarlet Knights jumped out to a 19-4 lead. Prince and Vaughn combined for 15 of the 19.

"It was just my teammates finding me," Vaughn said. "I was hot and you can't go away from that until they find a way to stop it"

Vaughn finished 6-for-7 from the field.

Army (5-5), which had won its last four games, was able to cut the deficit to 10, but could get no closer. Alex McGuire led Army with 16 points.

With Rutgers leading 33-21 at the break, Prince hit a 3-pointer to start the second half and ignite an 8-0 run. Brittany Ray capped the spurt with a 3 to make it 41-21. Army got no closer than 12 points the rest of the game despite holding Rutgers scoreless for over 6 minutes. Ray finished with 12 points.

Top-ranked Connecticut beat Penn State 77-63 in the second game of the doubleheader. Between games, all four teams stood on the court during a ceremony honoring Dixon.

Dixon died April 6, 2006, of arrhythmia, probably caused by an enlarged heart. Her death came three weeks after her first season as a head coach at Army, a performance that won the admiration of the academy and all of college basketball.

Last season Rutgers routed Army, and Duke edged Pitt in the first women's doubleheader at MSG since 1981, when Rutgers, Louisiana Tech, Old Dominion and Cheyney State took part.

The inaugural Maggie Dixon Classic was held at Army in 2006 -- a men's and women's doubleheader. Pitt's men's team -- coached by Maggie's brother Jamie, beat Western Michigan and Ohio State routed Army.

"It's really nice to see that it's taken the step to become bigger," McGuire said. "Hopefully it will remain one of the premier women's classics for years to come."

A portion of the proceeds from the games will go to C.A.R.E (Cardiac Arrhythmias Research and Education Foundation, Inc.). C.A.R.E. offered free heart screening for anyone attending the Classic.

Mayor Michael Bloomberg declared Sunday "Maggie Dixon Day" in New York City.
